                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <head>No. 344.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward Thornton</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1874-10-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 26, 1874</date>. (Received October
                        26.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of the 24th instant and to express my great regret that it has been
                    out of my power as yet to give a positive answer to your question with regard to
                    the political position of Labrador. I can, however, assure you that the delay
                    has not been caused by any neglect on the part of this legation.</p>
                <p>From information which I have received this morning, I am now enabled to state
                    positively that the whole of Labrador outside of the province of Quebec, the
                    boundary of which is laid down in the imperial statute, 6 George IV, ch. 59, is
                    under the jurisdiction and government of the colony of Newfoundland, and is
                    actually included in and forms a part of the colony.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>EDW’D THORNTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
